narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: The topics of this course are related to some of the largest unsolved problems in math like the Riemann Hypothesis and Birch Swinnerton-Dyer Conjecture.  We learned a good deal about infinite products, the gamma and zeta functions (and related functions like the beta function and a couple other L-functions), harmonic functions, the schwarz reflection principal, conformal maps and Christoffel Schwarz, and elliptic curves.  We also talked about some other topics which were less directly related to complex analysis, like differential forms and Riemann surfaces.  Some math courses just teach you math, but others make you a better mathematician.  This course is among the latter.

Infinite products, Weierstrass factorization theorem, Hadamard theorem, Harmonic Functions, Conformal Maps, Christoffel-Schwarz, Euler Gamma, Riemann Zeta, Weierstrass P, Elliptic functions, modular function, Schwarz Reflection principle and many other topics were discussed throughout the semester
Meromorphic functions, basic differential forms, infinite products, Gamma and Zeta functions, conformal maps, harmonic functions, reflection principle, Elliptic functions, Modular function
Gamma function, zeta function, elliptic function, modular forms, Schwarz reflection principle, Christoffel-Schwarz theorem, conformal mappings, Beta function, automorphism groups

Exposure to a variety of advanced concepts in complex analysis touching on areas of arithmetic, geometry, and even a little topology. These concepts went well beyond introductory complex analysis topics of contour integration, and included (but were not limited to) theorems of gamma functions, conformal mappings, and elliptic integrals).

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: The course material is incredibly cool, and Goncharov clearly loves it.  He's never bored, even though to him of course what we're learning is elementary.  The psets are fair and reinforce the material, and the midterm is also fair.  This course gives a nice picture of complex analysis and how different problems and fields fit together.   There are very few psets (only 5); this isn't good or bad necessarily, but maybe it's worth taking into account if you feel strongly either way about that and are considering the course.

The course has a very good structure. Professor Goncharov has notes that he seems to follow quite closely so that makes the lectures feel ordered. There are a lot of discussions that are spanned off of questions from students and professor Goncharov likes switching things up when they come up naturally in class. The lack of a textbook to reference is a bit difficult when you feel lost in the material but a few classic texts in complex analysis have good portions of what is covered in class.
Great survey course on advanced concepts in complex analysis that emphasized (mostly) beautiful geometric and arithmetic concepts of complex analysis rather than mechanical calculation.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: If you have a free slot, take this course.  It's not a 'must' in the same way some other courses are because it isn't a prerequisite for anything, but the material is a great payoff for what you did in 310.

If you're a math major (or maybe even physics) you should take this class. The workload isn't as bad as people make it to be and the exams (while tricky) are manageable. This class will make you a better mathematician and you'll walk out having a better idea of what math as a whole looks like. Professor Goncharov is a great lecturer and you're missing out if you don't take a class with him during your time here. The material of the course is also very beautiful. Professor Goncharov gives great geometric insight to complex analysis which changed the way I viewed the subject between 310 and 315.
Absolutely! It is a beautiful culmination of many fields of math. I do think it helps to take it later on though, since it brings in/touches on ideas from so many fields.
Absolutely. Math majors in the last two years of study will love this spectacular course.
If Prof. Goncharov is teaching, yes and hands down.
Definitely, especially if Prof Goncharov is teaching it  hes a great lecturer whos engaging and kind to his students.
